#compdef sqler
# ============================================================================
# sqler - turn SQL queries into safe RESTful APIs +
#          Redis Protocol (RESP) commands (Go,
#          Apache-2.0)
#
# Author : Mohammed Al Ashaal (alash3al)
# Upstream: https://github.com/alash3al/sqler
#
# `sqler` is a SQL-first API server: instead of
# writing a REST handler, an ORM mapping, and a
# DB query for each endpoint, you write a single
# HCL config file mapping HTTP route names to SQL
# macros (named multi-statement query blocks). The
# server exposes each macro as both:
#   - An HTTP REST endpoint (e.g. GET /macroName)
#   - A Redis-Protocol command (e.g. `MACRONAME
#     arg1 arg2` over a RESP connection)
#
# The server multiplexes a pool of database
# connections (configurable via `--workers`) +
# applies per-macro validation rules + authorization
# hooks. Macros can call JavaScript hooks
# (`include` directives) that execute via embedded
# goja JS runtime, with full access to a `resty`-
# backed HTTP client for outbound webhook calls
# + a SQL client for follow-up queries.
#
# Supported database drivers (all imported as
# blank imports in init.go):
#   - MySQL (go-sql-driver/mysql)
#   - PostgreSQL (lib/pq)
#   - SQLite3 (mattn/go-sqlite3)
#   - Microsoft SQL Server (denisenkom/go-mssqldb)
#   - ClickHouse (ClickHouse/clickhouse-go)
#   - SAP HANA (SAP/go-hdb)
#
# Use cases:
#   - Rapid REST-API prototyping for SQL-backed
#     services without writing Go handlers
#   - Database-as-a-Service exposure for legacy
#     SQL databases without rewriting them
#   - Webhook orchestration via JS-hook macros
#     (SQL query + outbound HTTP call in one
#     atomic macro)
#   - RESP-protocol gateway for monitoring tools
#     that already speak Redis
#
# Usage:
#   sqler [flags]
#
# Flags (Go stdlib `flag` declared in vars.go;
# single-dash style):
#   -driver <name>                 - SQL driver to
#                                     use (default
#                                     `mysql`;
#                                     valid:
#                                     mysql,
#                                     postgres,
#                                     sqlite3,
#                                     mssql,
#                                     clickhouse,
#                                     hdb)
#   -dsn <connection-string>       - DSN
#                                     connection
#                                     string for
#                                     the selected
#                                     driver
#                                     (default
#                                     `root:root@
#                                     tcp(127.0.0.1)
#                                     /test?
#                                     multiStatements
#                                     =true`)
#   -config <path>                 - config file
#                                     (or comma-
#                                     separated
#                                     glob patterns)
#                                     containing
#                                     endpoint
#                                     macros
#                                     (default
#                                     `./config.
#                                     example.hcl`)
#   -rest <addr>                   - HTTP REST API
#                                     listen
#                                     address
#                                     (default
#                                     `:8025`)
#   -resp <addr>                   - RESP (Redis
#                                     Protocol)
#                                     server
#                                     listen
#                                     address
#                                     (default
#                                     `:3678`)
#   -workers <n>                   - max worker
#                                     count (also
#                                     sets
#                                     GOMAXPROCS;
#                                     default
#                                     runtime.
#                                     NumCPU())
#   -sep <separator>               - multi-SQL
#                                     query
#                                     separator
#                                     in macros
#                                     (default
#                                     `---\\--`)
#   -h, -help                      - print help
#
# Example invocation:
#   sqler -driver postgres \
#         -dsn "postgres://user:pass@localhost/db?sslmode=disable" \
#         -config "./apis/*.hcl" \
#         -rest :8080 \
#         -workers 8
#
# Example HCL macro:
#   macro "users.list" {
#     exec = "SELECT id, name FROM users LIMIT ?LIMIT?"
#     methods = ["GET"]
#     include = "./hooks/audit.js"
#   }
#
# The go-resty/resty lane is built on
# `github.com/go-resty/resty/v2 v2.1.0` (declared
# verbatim at upstream go.mod HEAD as a direct dep,
# imported as `"github.com/go-resty/resty/v2"` in
# js.go line 8, then `client := resty.New()` at
# line 48 - the resty HTTP client is exposed to
# embedded JS macros for outbound HTTP calls), the
# canonical Go HTTP client library by Jeevanandam
# Madanagopal (jeevatkm) - github.com/go-resty/
# resty.
#
# Jeevanandam Madanagopal's go-resty/resty is the
# de-facto canonical Go HTTP client library
# (alongside the bare net/http stdlib + the
# higher-level alternatives like imroc/req +
# valyala/fasthttp):
#   - 10,000+ reverse-deps on pkg.go.dev
#   - Method-chaining fluent API for request
#     construction (axios-style ergonomics
#     ported to Go)
#   - Built on top of net/http (uses the
#     standard library's HTTP transport
#     internally)
#   - JSON + XML + form-data + multipart
#     serialization helpers
#   - Built-in retry + circuit-breaker support
#   - Connection pooling + transport
#     configuration
#   - Authentication helpers (basic auth,
#     bearer token, digest, OAuth2)
#   - Request/response middleware chain
#   - File upload + download with progress
#     callbacks
#   - Cookie jar + automatic redirect handling
#   - HTTP/2 support out-of-the-box (via
#     net/http transport)
#
# resty's distinguishing positioning vs the
# net/http stdlib:
#   - net/http: low-level; you write each request
#     by hand with http.Client + http.Request +
#     http.Response juggling
#   - resty: high-level; method chaining +
#     auto-JSON + pluggable middleware + retry
#     logic; trades verbosity for ergonomic
#     conciseness
#   - imroc/req: alternative high-level Go HTTP
#     client with slightly different API
#     conventions
#   - valyala/fasthttp: lower-level + faster
#     alternative to net/http (incompatible API);
#     not a higher-level wrapper
#
# Jeevanandam Madanagopal's broader Go ecosystem
# footprint:
#   - go-resty/resty (canonical Go HTTP client;
#     THIS AXIS)
#   - go-aah/aah (the aah web framework,
#     superseded by gin/echo in popularity but
#     historically significant)
#   - jeevatkm/go-model (struct mapping +
#     conversion library)
#   - jeevatkm/sslmate-go (SSL certificate
#     management bindings)
#
# Madanagopal's role differs from the Klaus Post
# (compress + reedsolomon + ...) and Niemeyer
# (yaml.v3 + gopkg.in) Go cohort - his canonical
# position is in *HTTP-client ergonomics* rather
# than systems libraries or serialization.
#
# sqler uses resty in js.go to provide outbound
# HTTP access to JavaScript macros:
#   ```go
#   import "github.com/go-resty/resty/v2"
#
#   func newJSContext() *goja.Runtime {
#       vm := goja.New()
#       client := resty.New()
#       vm.Set("http", client) // exposes resty
#       // to JS macros
#       return vm
#   }
#   ```
# JavaScript macros can then issue HTTP requests
# via `http.R().SetBody(payload).Post(url)` from
# within the macro, enabling integrations like
# "after this UPDATE, send a webhook to
# slack.example.com".
#
# ----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# AXIS 265 :: HTTP client libraries (high-level
#              ergonomic HTTP/HTTPS request
#              construction + response handling)
# Round 1494 :: Go slot 2 of 4 :: continues Axis 265
#
# Cross-language canonical library family for this axis:
#   Rust    : seanmonstar/reqwest        [R1493 _semtools]
#             (Sean McArthur; wraps
#              hyper)
#   Go      : go-resty/resty             [R1494 THIS FILE]
#             (Jeevanandam Madanagopal;
#              wraps net/http with
#              fluent API)
#   TS/Node : axios/axios                [R1495 closing]
#             (Matt Zabriskie; the
#              most-installed HTTP client
#              in any ecosystem)
#
# go-resty/resty is structurally interesting in
# this axis because it's the *ergonomic-wrapper-
# over-stdlib* canonical:
#   - The Go net/http stdlib already has a
#     complete HTTP client implementation
#   - resty doesn't replace net/http - it wraps
#     it with axios-style method chaining
#   - This is the *thin-ergonomic-layer* pattern
#     where the canonical library trades 20% of
#     net/http's flexibility for 80% of typical
#     use cases' ergonomic ease
#
# The three lanes form a clean spectrum of HTTP-
# client positioning:
#
#   - Rust (reqwest): wraps hyper; provides
#     high-level abstractions over McArthur's
#     own lower-level primitives; vertically-
#     integrated stack (same author throughout)
#   - Go (go-resty): wraps net/http stdlib;
#     provides ergonomic layer over the language's
#     bundled HTTP implementation
#   - Node (axios): isomorphic (works in both
#     browser + Node); the most-popular HTTP
#     client in *any* ecosystem; 50,000,000+
#     weekly npm downloads
#
# Cross-language interop at the HTTP wire-protocol
# level - all three libraries produce identical
# HTTP/1.1 + HTTP/2 requests on the wire that the
# same server can serve.
#
# Use-case spectrum across the three lanes (so
# far):
#   - semtools (Rust, reqwest): LlamaIndex
#     semantic-search CLI; reqwest for multipart
#     uploads to LlamaParse REST API
#   - sqler (Go, go-resty): SQL-to-REST API
#     server; resty exposed to embedded JS macros
#     for outbound webhook integration
#
# Notable that go-resty is in the *protocol-spec-
# bound canonical* axis (like axios + reqwest)
# rather than the fragmented-by-specialization
# axis (like SVG) because HTTP's spec is well-
# defined enough that ergonomic patterns
# (method chaining + JSON + middleware) are
# universal across implementations.
#
# Multi-axis canonical-Go author cohort (now
# spanning ~5 distinct individuals):
#   - Andrew Gerrand + the Go team (stdlib)
#   - Russ Cox (Go modules + crypto)
#   - Gustavo Niemeyer (yaml.v3 + gopkg.in
#     infrastructure)
#   - Klaus Post (compress + reedsolomon +
#     cpuid + asmfmt)
#   - Sergey Kamardin (gobwas/glob + gobwas/ws +
#     gobwas/httphead + gobwas/pool)
#   - Anthony Starks (ajstarks/svgo + deck +
#     dchart + openvg + gensvg)
#   - Jeevanandam Madanagopal (go-resty +
#     go-aah + go-model + sslmate-go, THIS AXIS)
#
# The Go canonical-author cohort skews toward
# *single-vertical mastery* (each author dominates
# one specialization niche) rather than
# horizontal-breadth like Tolnay in Rust.
# ============================================================================

_sqler() {
    local context state state_descr line
    typeset -A opt_args

    _arguments -s -S \
        '-driver=[SQL driver]:driver:(mysql postgres sqlite3 mssql clickhouse hdb)' \
        '-dsn=[DSN connection string]:dsn:' \
        '-config=[config file (or glob patterns)]:file:_files -g "*.hcl"' \
        '-rest=[HTTP REST API listen address]:addr:' \
        '-resp=[RESP (Redis Protocol) listen address]:addr:' \
        '-workers=[max worker count (also GOMAXPROCS)]:n:' \
        '-sep=[multi-SQL query separator in macros]:sep:' \
        '(- *)'{-h,-help}'[print help]'
}

_sqler "$@"
